<h1 class="hero-h">Fitagentic <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">vs Pike13.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">An honest comparison for small studios, personal training businesses, and swim/youth program operators. Pike13 has one of the friendliest CRM UXs in the category — and that simplicity is a real advantage. Fitagentic is the AI-native alternative for operators where lead response and retention matter more than scheduling simplicity.</p>
</div></div>

<div class="disclosure" style="max-width:880px;margin:1rem auto;">
<strong>Disclosure:</strong> Treetop Growth Strategy is the marketing and thought-leadership arm of Fitagentic.ai's parent company. We have a commercial interest in Fitagentic. Pike13 gets real wins below — that's how an honest comparison reads.
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The TL;DR</span>
<h2 class="h2">The honest answer</h2>
<p class="body"><strong>Pike13 is the stronger choice if</strong> you value simple scheduling above all else, your business model is high-touch personal training where the trainer-client relationship is the product (and tech should stay out of the way), or you're a swim/youth/family program with complex enrollment patterns Pike13 handles well.</p>
<p class="body"><strong>Fitagentic is the stronger choice if</strong> you're past 50 active clients and lead response or member retention is becoming a bottleneck — or if you want AI agents handling the admin and conversation work so trainers can train.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Where Pike13 wins</span>
<h2 class="h2">The Pike13 case</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Friendliest UX in the category.</strong> Pike13 is one of the easiest gym CRMs to set up and run day-to-day. For owner-operators who want to spend zero time fighting their software, this is real.</li>
<li><strong>Simple scheduling and billing.</strong> Recurring memberships, packages, drop-ins, simple class scheduling — clean and predictable.</li>
<li><strong>Swim / youth / family program fit.</strong> Pike13 handles the enrollment patterns and family-account complexity of youth programs better than most general fitness CRMs.</li>
<li><strong>Lower learning curve for non-technical owners.</strong> Less to misconfigure, less to break, less staff training.</li>
<li><strong>Reasonable pricing for very small businesses.</strong> Entry tier is well-suited to single-trainer or 2-3 person operations.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Where Fitagentic wins</span>
<h2 class="h2">The Fitagentic case</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>AI-native architecture.</strong> Pike13 has marketing automation; Fitagentic has agents. Lead nurture is conversational; no-show recovery is automatic; retention is proactive.</li>
<li><strong>Sub-60-second lead response.</strong> Pike13's lead capture forms route to email; the trainer responds when they have time. Fitagentic responds in seconds with a real conversation.</li>
<li><strong>Trainer-time displacement.</strong> The single biggest opportunity for personal training studios above 50 clients — Fitagentic absorbs the lead, scheduling, and FAQ conversations so trainers can train.</li>
<li><strong>Member retention agents.</strong> Pike13 has reporting; Fitagentic acts on it. Particularly valuable for personal training where one cancelled client is a meaningful revenue hit.</li>
<li><strong>Scales beyond Pike13's sweet spot.</strong> Pike13 starts to feel limited around 200+ active clients; Fitagentic stays performant well into multi-location.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Side-by-side</span>
<h2 class="h2">Honest feature comparison</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Pike13</th><th>Fitagentic</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>UX simplicity for non-technical owner</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong></td><td>Simple but more powerful surface</td></tr>
<tr><td>Family + youth program enrollment</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong></td><td>Adequate</td></tr>
<tr><td>Recurring billing</td><td>Solid</td><td>Solid</td></tr>
<tr><td>Lead response speed + quality</td><td>Email-based, hours</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong> — under 60 seconds</td></tr>
<tr><td>No-show recovery</td><td>Manual</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong> — first-class workflow</td></tr>
<tr><td>Member retention agents</td><td>Reporting only</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong></td></tr>
<tr><td>Trainer-time displacement</td><td>Modest</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong> — material</td></tr>
<tr><td>Scales above 200 active clients</td><td>Adequate</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong></td></tr>
<tr><td>Software-line monthly cost</td><td>$129+ scaling with clients</td><td>$250-$1,000/loc</td></tr>
<tr><td>Total cost of ownership for growing studio</td><td>Lower until ~50 clients</td><td><strong>Stronger</strong> past ~50 clients</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
</div></section>

